WEBVTT

00:08.667 --> 00:11.200
The best part of this is,
it's not a dream.

00:16.100 --> 00:19.166
The worst part, it's CPR class.

00:20.900 --> 00:22.734
Yo, coach. What do I do now?

00:24.967 --> 00:26.000
Kiss me, you fool.

00:26.734 --> 00:28.100
Blow in my mouth.

00:28.400 --> 00:31.266
Craft, we have been
over this 15 times.

00:32.900 --> 00:34.000
Take a seat.

00:35.300 --> 00:37.867
Tudgeman, front and center.

00:38.567 --> 00:40.033
Oh. No, no, no.

00:40.433 --> 00:41.834
Maybe I should take a seat too.

00:41.900 --> 00:44.066
Give someone else a chance
to be a choking victim.

00:44.133 --> 00:45.166
On the floor, McGuire.

00:45.500 --> 00:46.500
Could I run laps instead?

00:46.633 --> 00:50.133
You can run laps in addition to,
on the floor, McGuire.

00:51.567 --> 00:52.567
Tudgeman.

00:54.667 --> 00:55.967
Make us proud.

00:56.100 --> 00:57.133
[ALL CHUCKLING]

00:57.200 --> 00:59.233
Ooh. Looks like
my junior firefighting course

00:59.300 --> 01:00.467
is finally paying off.

01:01.400 --> 01:03.100
Lips, don't fail me now.

01:04.033 --> 01:05.200
[KISSING]

01:05.300 --> 01:07.166
LIZZIE: Oh, my God. Ew.

01:07.233 --> 01:09.600
Let me die.

01:09.900 --> 01:11.934
[THEME MUSIC PLAYING]

01:52.433 --> 01:53.600
Mint, mint.

01:54.300 --> 01:55.700
You're gonna be okay, Lizzie.

01:55.767 --> 01:57.567
It was only CPR class.

01:57.633 --> 02:00.166
It's not like Tudgeman
actually kissed you.

02:00.233 --> 02:03.000
Hey, Lizzie.
I heard that you kissed Tudgeman.

02:03.066 --> 02:04.834
So, where are you two
going on your honeymoon?

02:04.900 --> 02:06.967
[LAUGHS]

02:07.800 --> 02:10.433
Why does Ethan Craft
have to be so dumb?

02:10.734 --> 02:13.066
Squeeze and blow, it's not that hard.

02:13.400 --> 02:15.333
Maybe he has a lot on his mind.

02:15.834 --> 02:17.400
Why did we have
to learn mouth to mouth

02:17.467 --> 02:18.700
and the Heimlich maneuver anyway?

02:18.767 --> 02:20.734
It's not like I plan on
being a lifeguard.

02:20.800 --> 02:22.700
What do we ever learn
here that's useful?

02:22.767 --> 02:25.333
How to make Mock Apple Pie
out of salty crackers.

02:25.400 --> 02:26.400
Mmm-hmm.

02:26.467 --> 02:29.400
It's official, we're the only
three kids in this school

02:29.467 --> 02:32.300
who haven't seen
<i>Vesuvius: The Eruption.</i>

02:32.367 --> 02:33.867
Duh, 'cause it's rated R.

02:33.934 --> 02:36.066
Besides, Gordo, since when do
you care what other people do?

02:36.166 --> 02:38.200
I don't. I just wanna see the movie.

02:38.266 --> 02:41.300
An entire ancient city
destroyed by lava and...

02:41.400 --> 02:44.266
And, Ben Affleck
in a doomed love affair.

02:44.600 --> 02:47.033
I know you're right.
It's like the best movie ever made.

02:47.100 --> 02:48.600
Why does it have to be rated R?

02:48.667 --> 02:52.400
Because of adult situations,
mild violence, and brief nudity.

02:52.467 --> 02:54.200
This is so unfair.
I mean, if I can handle

02:54.266 --> 02:56.300
mouth to mouth with Larry Tudgeman,

02:58.400 --> 03:00.600
I think I can handle
<i>Vesuvius: The Eruption.</i>

03:00.667 --> 03:03.433
You locked lips with Larry Tudgeman?

03:03.500 --> 03:05.500
Health class. It was required.

03:06.033 --> 03:08.200
Nothing good ever happens
in health class. Ugh.

03:09.033 --> 03:10.700
The movies they show us,
give us nightmares.

03:10.767 --> 03:13.500
I cannot believe they make us watch
a women smoke through her throat,

03:13.567 --> 03:15.400
but I can't see
<i>Vesuvius: The Eruption.</i>

03:15.700 --> 03:17.633
You know what?
You're absolutely right.

03:17.867 --> 03:19.333
I say, we go see it.

03:19.400 --> 03:22.233
-I'm free Saturday afternoon.
-Coolie. I'm in too.

03:22.667 --> 03:25.800
Great. So, we're gonna go see
an R rated movie.

03:25.867 --> 03:26.867
It's about time.

03:26.934 --> 03:28.633
I'm totally mature enough
to see an R rated movie.

03:28.700 --> 03:32.000
-Absolutely.
-Great. So, let's do it.

03:32.066 --> 03:33.433
We'll just go.

03:33.834 --> 03:36.200
Great, so, uh,
whose parents are gonna take us?

03:36.867 --> 03:38.867
[SCOFFS] Who are we kidding?

03:38.934 --> 03:40.800
-[SIGHS] We're doomed.
-[SCHOOL BELL RINGS]

03:40.967 --> 03:42.967
There's no way
our parents are gonna let us go.

03:43.033 --> 03:45.700
Of course, not. If that's
our attitude when we ask them.

03:45.900 --> 03:47.066
LIZZIE: Why bother asking?

03:47.133 --> 03:49.400
My mom won't let me wear
tops that show my stomach.

03:49.467 --> 03:51.533
She'll never let me see
an R rated movie.

03:51.800 --> 03:53.667
Fine. Let's not try.

03:54.033 --> 03:56.367
Let's just spend
the next four years of our lives

03:56.633 --> 03:59.033
watching movies about
talking animals and cartoon elves

03:59.100 --> 04:00.500
and call ourselves happy.

04:00.967 --> 04:04.266
I don't think I can stand
one more talking pig movie.

04:05.066 --> 04:06.967
Okay, we'll try.

04:07.100 --> 04:08.600
Good, we can do this.

04:08.934 --> 04:10.734
We just need
to handle it in the right way.

04:11.200 --> 04:13.600
And, make sure we're on the same page.

04:14.000 --> 04:15.633
Maybe I should write this down.

04:18.266 --> 04:19.266
[CLEARS THROAT]

04:25.567 --> 04:27.233
Mom, Dad.

04:27.567 --> 04:31.066
I've been reading the reviews on
this new movie <i>Vesuvius: The Eruption.</i>

04:31.133 --> 04:33.533
It turns out there's a lot
of historical information in it.

04:34.100 --> 04:36.233
So, it would be beneficial
for me on lots of levels.

04:36.300 --> 04:37.834
Because, the emotional issues

04:37.900 --> 04:39.400
involved in
Ben Affleck's forbidden love...

04:39.467 --> 04:41.400
...with a peasant girl,
not of his station...

04:41.467 --> 04:44.100
...mirrors certain
socio-economic issues.

04:44.166 --> 04:45.700
In our own society today.

04:45.900 --> 04:47.633
And, even though it's rated R.

04:47.700 --> 04:50.100
It's not that inappropriate
for kids my age to see it.

04:50.166 --> 04:52.066
And, all the other kids
at school have seen it.

04:52.133 --> 04:54.100
And, it's all anybody
ever talks about.

04:54.867 --> 04:56.300
-So...
-ALL: Can I see it?

04:56.700 --> 04:57.734
BOTH: No.

04:58.934 --> 05:01.867
Lizzie is way too young
to see an R rated movie.

05:02.166 --> 05:04.533
Sounds like a cool movie though.
Maybe we should go see it.

05:06.300 --> 05:07.700
What? We're over 17.

05:08.433 --> 05:09.500
Mom, Dad.

05:09.567 --> 05:12.433
Mrs. McNamara is so excited
you're building a booth

05:12.500 --> 05:13.800
for the school carnival.

05:14.567 --> 05:15.567
We are?

05:15.633 --> 05:17.133
I thought
we were blowing up balloons.

05:17.200 --> 05:19.967
No, I volunteered
you guys to build a booth.

05:20.033 --> 05:22.600
And, I want you guys
to make something really cool.

05:22.667 --> 05:25.033
Oh, honey.
Last time we did something cool,

05:25.100 --> 05:26.800
your dad got his eyebrows burned off.

05:27.700 --> 05:29.533
And they grew back sort of funny, too.

05:29.600 --> 05:31.367
No, I like your new eyebrows.

05:31.433 --> 05:35.433
But, Jeff Thompson and his parents
are building a dunk tank.

05:35.934 --> 05:37.533
Wait a minute, Jeff Thompson.

05:38.000 --> 05:40.166
Isn't he the one
with the mother whose cookies

05:40.233 --> 05:42.166
always come in first at the bake sale?

05:48.200 --> 05:51.800
Yeah, but, I guess
we could just blow up balloons.

05:52.700 --> 05:54.500
It'll be fun.

05:55.033 --> 05:56.800
No, no, no. We can build a booth.

05:57.767 --> 05:58.767
What do you have in mind?

05:58.867 --> 06:01.100
Okay. So, people come up to the booth

06:01.166 --> 06:02.800
and stand up against a wall

06:02.867 --> 06:04.533
with an apple on their head.

06:05.100 --> 06:07.834
I don't... I don't see
the game here, honey.

06:07.900 --> 06:11.800
Then, Dad shoots the apple off
their head with a flaming arrow.

06:12.166 --> 06:14.967
Very William Tell.
Historical, I like it.

06:15.734 --> 06:16.734
Sam?

06:18.033 --> 06:21.100
Fine, um,
we shouldn't shoot flaming arrows

06:21.166 --> 06:23.266
-at people's heads, son.
-[GASPS]

06:23.433 --> 06:26.967
-But, what if the arrow isn't flaming?
-Yeah.

06:27.033 --> 06:27.967
No.

06:30.834 --> 06:34.033
But, I wanna do something extreme.

06:34.433 --> 06:37.867
What have you got all over
your new cargo pants?

06:38.100 --> 06:40.834
If you wanna do something extreme,
let's just take it down a notch.

06:40.900 --> 06:42.834
We could have, uh,
milk bottles lined up

06:42.900 --> 06:45.100
instead of throwing baseballs,
we could throw frisbees at 'em.

06:45.166 --> 06:46.166
That'll be extreme.

06:46.433 --> 06:48.633
Yeah, extremely lame.

06:51.066 --> 06:52.266
I have an idea.

06:54.433 --> 06:57.667
How about we build a Velcro wall.

06:58.300 --> 06:59.734
A Velcro wall?

07:01.467 --> 07:02.567
Talk to me.

07:02.633 --> 07:05.800
Well, people will pay good money
to put on a Velcro suit

07:05.867 --> 07:08.567
and go run and jump
and stick to a Velcro wall.

07:09.767 --> 07:11.533
You know, I like how she thinks.

07:12.000 --> 07:13.867
That's why I married her, son.

07:14.567 --> 07:16.633
Yeah, Mom, you rock.

07:16.900 --> 07:18.100
It's true. I do.

07:18.166 --> 07:19.567
Son, we've got a wall to build.

07:19.633 --> 07:22.800
Yes. We're gonna have
the coolest booth in the carnival.

07:22.867 --> 07:24.967
Yes, yes, yes, yes.

07:26.333 --> 07:27.333
Hey.

07:27.834 --> 07:30.767
Oh, hey. I was thinking,
since we can't go to the movies

07:30.834 --> 07:32.867
this weekend, we should
got to Mount Rushmore minigolf.

07:34.200 --> 07:37.734
Miniature golf? Is that
the dorkiest thing you can think of?

07:37.800 --> 07:40.333
How about the sci-fi convention?

07:41.100 --> 07:43.166
Hey, I like miniature golf, okay?

07:43.233 --> 07:45.433
You're just still mad about
your fourth grade birthday party,

07:45.500 --> 07:47.066
when I set
the course record for windmill.

07:49.000 --> 07:50.000
I can't believe that I'm saying this,

07:50.066 --> 07:52.333
but <i>Vesuvius</i> is actually
better than <i>Star Wars.</i>

07:52.400 --> 07:55.100
I've seen it four times
and I still can't figure out

07:55.166 --> 07:56.600
how they do that thing with the lava.

07:57.000 --> 08:01.033
[SNORTS] I'm not watching the lava,
I'm watching the slave girls.

08:01.100 --> 08:02.233
Yeah.

08:02.300 --> 08:03.500
Oh, Lizzie.

08:06.800 --> 08:07.800
Gross.

08:09.100 --> 08:10.300
Okay, new plan.

08:10.367 --> 08:12.367
We tell our parents
we're going miniature golfing,

08:12.433 --> 08:15.033
and when instead,
we go and see <i>Vesuvius.</i>

08:15.333 --> 08:17.800
Okay. So, you're telling me
to lie to my parents?

08:17.967 --> 08:20.100
No, I'm asking you
to make a last minute change

08:20.166 --> 08:21.667
in plans in advance.

08:21.934 --> 08:23.834
Hmm, that sounds reasonable to me.

08:24.700 --> 08:26.700
Okay, I'll try.

08:27.000 --> 08:28.266
But, I don't think it's gonna work.

08:33.400 --> 08:34.567
This is never gonna work.

08:41.233 --> 08:42.233
Mom?

08:43.800 --> 08:45.033
Can I ask you something?

08:45.100 --> 08:46.467
This is never gonna work.

08:47.166 --> 08:48.500
Sure, sweetie. What's up?

08:50.066 --> 08:53.300
Uh, can I go play miniature golf
with Gordo and Miranda this weekend?

08:54.200 --> 08:56.033
This is never gonna work.

08:56.367 --> 08:58.200
Sure. That sounds fun.

08:58.967 --> 09:00.033
What?

09:00.934 --> 09:02.033
Yes!

09:06.567 --> 09:08.100
We can't all go up together.

09:08.166 --> 09:09.333
Why not?

09:09.400 --> 09:11.934
Because if they turn us
all down, we're dead.

09:12.166 --> 09:14.500
But, if we go one at a time,
we'll have three shots at this, right?

09:16.500 --> 09:17.834
Fine, I'll go first.

09:17.900 --> 09:19.000
[SIGHS]

09:19.066 --> 09:20.300
-Good luck.
-Good luck.

09:21.800 --> 09:24.900
Good afternoon, uh,
my fiancÃ© and her friend

09:24.967 --> 09:26.633
are parking the car outside,

09:26.700 --> 09:28.533
and I was picking up
the tickets for them.

09:31.100 --> 09:33.033
Is the 1:30 show sold out yet?

09:33.100 --> 09:34.533
My college teacher's making me,

09:34.600 --> 09:36.033
'cause she wants me
to write a paper on it.

09:36.100 --> 09:38.233
I tell you, boy,
do I need this day off.

09:38.300 --> 09:40.900
If it is, the 4:00 show
it'd be okay too.

09:40.967 --> 09:43.600
The boss is just busting
my hump down at the office.

09:43.667 --> 09:47.233
And, working at a law firm,
part time is no picnic.

09:49.300 --> 09:50.800
-Ben.
-Uh...

09:50.867 --> 09:51.867
Um...

09:51.934 --> 09:53.467
-Boy, do I...
-Hey.

09:53.667 --> 09:54.900
Oh, not sold out?

09:55.333 --> 09:56.800
I guess I'll take three tickets then.

09:57.133 --> 09:58.266
So, if you could just...

10:00.233 --> 10:01.834
$7.50 each?

10:02.200 --> 10:04.000
Isn't there, like,
an under 14 discount?

10:08.600 --> 10:09.633
No.

10:10.266 --> 10:11.467
[SIGHS] No luck.

10:12.100 --> 10:14.000
Okay, revised new plan.

10:14.200 --> 10:15.800
If they're not gonna sell us
any tickets,

10:16.100 --> 10:18.066
we'll just sneak in through the back.

10:18.433 --> 10:21.467
Sneak in? Isn't that like stealing?

10:21.533 --> 10:24.233
Yeah, but we're gonna
give them great word of mouth

10:24.300 --> 10:25.800
so a lot more people
will see the movie.

10:26.100 --> 10:27.633
In a way we're doing them a favor

10:28.033 --> 10:30.567
Plus, we'll just buy a bunch of
stuff at the concession stand.

10:30.633 --> 10:32.467
I mean, that's where they make
all their money, anyway.

10:34.300 --> 10:35.767
I guess that kinda makes sense.

10:36.200 --> 10:37.667
It's my law school training.

10:37.734 --> 10:39.100
[CHUCKLING]

10:39.166 --> 10:40.166
[SIGHS]

10:44.333 --> 10:45.800
How can the fire exit be locked?

10:46.166 --> 10:47.767
I mean that can't be good.

10:47.834 --> 10:49.266
So, what do we do now?

10:49.333 --> 10:50.533
I say we go home.

10:50.633 --> 10:52.033
I mean, <i>Vesuvius</i> can wait.

10:52.100 --> 10:53.100
No, it can't.

10:53.166 --> 10:54.500
It's Ben Affleck, Lizzie.

10:54.667 --> 10:58.667
Ben Affleck. Sweating
in clingy Roman clothes.

10:58.867 --> 11:00.000
Okay, here's what we do.

11:00.066 --> 11:01.734
We wait for the current show
to let out,

11:01.934 --> 11:03.867
and then while everyone's
leaving the theatre, come on.

11:05.166 --> 11:08.100
All right, guys, talk like
you just saw the movie.

11:08.166 --> 11:09.266
Okay.

11:09.467 --> 11:10.767
The critics are right.

11:10.834 --> 11:13.300
<i>Vesuvius</i> explodes off the screen.

11:13.367 --> 11:15.500
Another triumph for Ben Affleck.

11:15.567 --> 11:17.433
His love scenes are hotter than lava.

11:17.867 --> 11:20.200
Don't hail Caesar, hail Oscar.

11:20.266 --> 11:21.433
I like the volcano.

11:22.400 --> 11:24.300
What? I-I like volcanoes.

11:25.900 --> 11:27.133
Okay, we're in.

11:27.200 --> 11:28.367
Everybody hide in the restroom

11:28.433 --> 11:29.700
and meet back here in five minutes.

11:29.767 --> 11:30.767
Okay.

11:30.867 --> 11:31.867
All right. Come on.

11:31.934 --> 11:33.533
How does it feel? Is it snug?

11:33.600 --> 11:35.033
Really comfortable.

11:35.300 --> 11:36.700
I could wear this all the time.

11:36.767 --> 11:38.367
Well, let's see
if it works first, okay?

11:38.433 --> 11:43.633
Ladies and gentlemen,
boys and girls, children of all ages,

11:43.834 --> 11:49.633
prepare to be awestruck by
Velcro-boy the flying McGuire.

11:52.033 --> 11:53.100
Can't get up.

11:54.100 --> 11:56.367
Sam? A little help inside, please.

11:59.467 --> 12:01.600
I'll have a large popcorn,
a root beer.

12:02.100 --> 12:04.867
Ooh, sour gummy worms,
malted milk balls.

12:05.200 --> 12:07.867
Okay, I didn't buy
an eight dollar ticket.

12:08.033 --> 12:10.266
But, I'm spending 17 bucks on popcorn.

12:10.934 --> 12:12.333
Butter flavoring on the popcorn?

12:12.400 --> 12:13.600
Only if it costs extra.

12:13.767 --> 12:15.600
[MAN COUGHING]

12:17.333 --> 12:20.033
I can't believe we're gonna
go see an R rated movie.

12:20.367 --> 12:22.066
Today, I'm a man.

12:23.200 --> 12:28.133
Jeremy? Je... Jeremy?
Jeremy's choking.

12:29.333 --> 12:30.567
Come on, somebody get help.

12:30.867 --> 12:32.033
Oh, my gosh.

12:33.767 --> 12:35.000
Somebody do something.

12:35.333 --> 12:37.533
Lizzie, you've had the CPR classes.

12:39.266 --> 12:40.567
Help that guy.

12:42.000 --> 12:43.166
Somebody besides me.

12:45.433 --> 12:47.300
-But... No, but...
-Go. Go. Lizzie, help that guy.

12:54.500 --> 12:56.033
[COUGHING]

13:08.667 --> 13:09.667
Ugh.

13:11.667 --> 13:13.100
Hey, you want this?

13:16.200 --> 13:17.300
Thank you so much.

13:17.600 --> 13:20.200
I-I told him to slow down
on the sour balls.

13:20.266 --> 13:21.300
Ugh.

13:21.367 --> 13:22.834
I'm just glad
you were here to save him.

13:22.934 --> 13:25.734
Wow. Something I learned
in school actually paid off.

13:26.767 --> 13:28.967
See, Lizzie. If you hadn't
lied to your parents

13:29.033 --> 13:30.867
and snuck into an R rated movie,

13:31.000 --> 13:32.600
that guy would have choked to death.

13:33.300 --> 13:34.333
I love you, man.

13:37.567 --> 13:38.567
Bye.

13:38.934 --> 13:40.467
I'm a hero.

13:41.100 --> 13:43.700
Well, I learned CPR
in school and I just reacted.

13:44.300 --> 13:46.266
And, I told her to save the guy.

13:46.333 --> 13:48.033
And, I was on board
with it right away.

13:48.367 --> 13:49.934
[CHUCKLES] So, there you have it.

13:50.000 --> 13:52.166
A real life matinee hero.

13:52.400 --> 13:55.533
From the 1:30 showing of <i>Vesuvius,</i>
I'm Kirka Johansson.

13:56.700 --> 13:59.000
-So cool.
-All right, thank you.

14:00.800 --> 14:03.066
This is so cool.
You guys, we're gonna be on TV.

14:05.100 --> 14:06.400
This could be my big break.

14:06.467 --> 14:10.233
Next, I'll be starring opposite
Ben Affleck in <i>Vesuvius-Two.</i>

14:10.433 --> 14:12.033
We have to get home and tape it.

14:12.100 --> 14:13.100
Oh, yeah.

14:13.166 --> 14:14.200
Um, Lizzie, Miranda.

14:14.900 --> 14:16.133
We're gonna be on TV.

14:16.934 --> 14:18.100
Yeah, we know.

14:18.467 --> 14:21.066
We're gonna be on TV
in the lobby of the rated R movie

14:21.133 --> 14:22.867
that we snuck into
while all of our parents

14:22.934 --> 14:24.300
thought we were playing
miniature golf?

14:25.800 --> 14:26.800
Oh.

14:28.133 --> 14:30.700
Or, I could be starring in
<i>Grounded Forever,</i>

14:30.767 --> 14:32.100
<i>the Lizzie McGuire story.</i>

14:32.867 --> 14:35.133
We need to get home and make sure
our parents don't watch the news.

14:35.200 --> 14:36.734
This is so unfair.

14:36.800 --> 14:39.266
I saved someone's life
and I'm gonna end up in trouble.

14:41.166 --> 14:42.367
[SIGHS]

14:45.033 --> 14:47.700
And, thank you also
for the free movie passes

14:47.767 --> 14:48.867
and the...and the gift certificate.

14:48.934 --> 14:49.934
That's fantastic.

14:50.300 --> 14:52.166
Okay, thanks, bye, bye.

14:53.400 --> 14:54.433
Who was that, honey?

14:54.600 --> 14:57.633
It was the manager
from the Wilco movie theatre.

14:57.967 --> 15:00.533
Lizzie saved
someone's life down there.

15:00.600 --> 15:03.867
A guy was choking and she gave him
the Heimlich maneuver,

15:03.934 --> 15:05.266
she saved his life.

15:05.333 --> 15:06.333
You're kidding.

15:06.400 --> 15:08.667
No, it's gonna be
on 6:00 news and everything.

15:08.934 --> 15:11.633
Wow. Our daughter, the hero.

15:14.266 --> 15:15.400
Wait a second.

15:15.467 --> 15:17.100
Did she say the Wilco theatre?

15:17.166 --> 15:18.633
Isn't that where <i>Vesuvius</i> is playing?

15:20.900 --> 15:21.900
Yeah, it is.

15:23.033 --> 15:25.433
She told me
she was playing miniature golf.

15:25.934 --> 15:28.734
Our daughter may be a hero,
but she's a lying hero.

15:29.100 --> 15:31.066
[MATT YELLING]

15:33.667 --> 15:35.834
You might wanna wait
till I put the Velcro up, son.

15:36.100 --> 15:38.500
MATT: Thanks for the heads up, Dad.

15:39.200 --> 15:40.700
[GROANS]

15:41.967 --> 15:43.100
Okay, here is the plan.

15:43.166 --> 15:44.200
You had another?

15:44.266 --> 15:46.433
How about a plan
that actually works this time.

15:46.767 --> 15:48.166
We have to prevent
your parents from seeing

15:48.233 --> 15:49.967
the six o'clock news at all costs.

15:50.033 --> 15:52.467
That's not a plan. That's a goal.

15:52.633 --> 15:54.233
Fine, new goal then.

15:54.700 --> 15:56.467
Well, maybe they won't
watch the news tonight.

15:56.533 --> 15:58.100
Maybe they won't see the interview

15:58.166 --> 15:59.400
and this'll all go away.

15:59.467 --> 16:01.033
Nah. Not gonna happen.

16:01.100 --> 16:02.333
My parents never miss the news.

16:02.400 --> 16:05.000
My mom gets all weepy
at the adopt a pet segment.

16:05.300 --> 16:07.834
Hey, kids. How was miniature golf?

16:08.300 --> 16:10.667
-Um, great.
-Fun.

16:10.734 --> 16:13.166
Really good. I-I had
the bright yellow ball.

16:13.500 --> 16:14.800
-Yeah.
-Who won?

16:14.867 --> 16:15.867
-Gordo.
-Miranda.

16:15.934 --> 16:16.934
Lizzie.

16:17.934 --> 16:19.367
It was a tie.

16:19.433 --> 16:22.533
Yeah, we never really understood
how that whole scoring thing works.

16:22.600 --> 16:24.433
Besides, we're all winners here.

16:24.500 --> 16:25.800
Oh yeah. Mmm-hmm.

16:25.867 --> 16:28.433
I'm so glad that you guys
had fun playing miniature golf.

16:28.500 --> 16:30.767
Hey, you know, we should play
miniature golf more often.

16:30.834 --> 16:32.767
We should. You know, maybe
we should go this weekend.

16:32.834 --> 16:34.867
-Oh, but, you guys just went.
-Yeah.

16:34.934 --> 16:36.967
Oh, oh, we'd go again.

16:37.133 --> 16:39.066
You know what,
we would go right now even.

16:39.133 --> 16:40.567
Yeah, let's go right now.

16:40.633 --> 16:42.200
Right now.
That, that's a great idea...

16:42.266 --> 16:43.300
You know, I don't know.

16:43.367 --> 16:45.066
-I-I heard it might rain.
-Oh, I heard that too.

16:45.133 --> 16:47.834
You know, maybe
we should turn on the news

16:47.934 --> 16:49.867
to hear what
the weather report is, huh?

16:49.934 --> 16:52.233
-That's a great idea.
-LIZZIE: No. No, no.

16:52.333 --> 16:54.133
Aah. They-they're always
wrong anyways.

16:54.200 --> 16:55.900
Yeah. Uh, we should just go.
I call shotgun.

16:55.967 --> 16:58.467
-I call bright yellow ball.
-No, let's watch the news.

16:58.533 --> 17:00.967
-No, wait.
-Sweetie, what's wrong?

17:01.033 --> 17:04.867
Uh, the-the sports guy,
he'll announce who won the car races

17:04.934 --> 17:06.767
and Gordo's taping it at home,

17:06.834 --> 17:08.834
and he doesn't wanna
know who the winner is.

17:08.900 --> 17:10.133
[INHALES] Right, Gordo?

17:10.400 --> 17:12.934
Yeah, I-I love car races.

17:13.233 --> 17:14.500
Really, Gordo?

17:14.567 --> 17:16.567
I had no idea that
you were a racing nut.

17:16.700 --> 17:19.333
What're you into, NASCAR? Formula 1?

17:19.400 --> 17:24.834
All, all of them.
NASCAR, Formula 1, Formula 2, uh,

17:24.900 --> 17:26.567
nitro powered funny cars.

17:27.066 --> 17:28.066
[IMITATES CAR ENGINE]

17:28.433 --> 17:29.700
What... you know what we can do?

17:29.767 --> 17:31.867
We can turn off the TV
before the sports

17:31.934 --> 17:33.867
because they always save
that for the end anyway.

17:33.934 --> 17:34.967
Yeah.

17:37.467 --> 17:38.800
-[GASPS]
-Lizzie.

17:39.233 --> 17:41.433
I'm sorry. I'm such a klutz.

17:42.166 --> 17:43.300
I loved that lamp.

17:44.000 --> 17:46.166
We can glue it back together.

17:46.233 --> 17:48.467
Yeah. Everyone,
help me pick up the pieces.

17:49.200 --> 17:50.467
Kids, you can leave that.

17:51.133 --> 17:55.367
No, no. Uh, um, this was
Dad's favorite lamp, Mom.

17:55.433 --> 17:58.734
So, um, we're gonna have
to into the kitchen and...

17:59.867 --> 18:01.500
pick it up, glue it back together.

18:01.567 --> 18:03.100
-All of us together.
-MIRANDA: Right. Yes.

18:03.166 --> 18:05.967
Honey, forget about the lamp.

18:06.133 --> 18:08.967
Jo, I really did like that lamp.

18:09.000 --> 18:10.066
Why can't we fix it?

18:10.367 --> 18:12.133
Because we don't have time.

18:13.000 --> 18:16.767
Because we have to watch the news
to see if it's going to rain,

18:17.367 --> 18:18.934
to see if we can play miniature golf.

18:19.300 --> 18:20.367
Right.

18:20.433 --> 18:22.967
But, you see it's not going
to rain because my big toe

18:23.033 --> 18:24.400
always hurts when it's gonna rain.

18:26.233 --> 18:29.233
And, right now it feel great,
so we can go.

18:29.400 --> 18:30.600
Come on, let's move it on out.

18:30.667 --> 18:31.667
You know what?

18:32.367 --> 18:34.133
I don't feel like playing
miniature golf anymore.

18:34.734 --> 18:35.967
I feel like going to the movies.

18:36.033 --> 18:37.567
SAM: That is a great idea.

18:37.767 --> 18:38.767
Huh?

18:38.834 --> 18:41.000
Yeah, um, there's this
talking dog flick out

18:41.066 --> 18:42.734
that I, I really want to catch.

18:42.800 --> 18:45.567
It seems that his master has been
spending too much time

18:45.633 --> 18:47.834
at the office, neglecting
the wife and the kids,

18:48.133 --> 18:51.166
and the talking dog
shows him the error of his ways.

18:51.233 --> 18:52.567
You know what I really want to see?

18:53.533 --> 18:54.600
<i>Vesuvius.</i>

18:56.900 --> 18:58.000
Oh, yeah.

18:59.300 --> 19:01.367
But, I thought you said
we couldn't see that movie.

19:01.433 --> 19:04.000
Well, Lizzie, your mother
and I have been discussing this,

19:04.567 --> 19:06.867
and we feel that you guys
are mature enough

19:06.934 --> 19:08.233
to enjoy that movie.

19:08.300 --> 19:09.767
And, you can't get in without us.

19:09.834 --> 19:11.867
-Right?
-[CHUCKLES]

19:14.567 --> 19:16.166
You think they know?

19:16.934 --> 19:18.800
Oh, yeah, Lizzie.

19:19.967 --> 19:21.200
BOTH: We know.

19:21.734 --> 19:22.967
Oh. [GROANS]

19:26.000 --> 19:27.867
Oh. So, uh, how busted are you?

19:28.533 --> 19:30.200
Busted like gnome lamp.

19:30.400 --> 19:31.567
You?

19:31.633 --> 19:34.266
Uh, my parents
are very "disappointed" in me.

19:34.533 --> 19:36.300
I hate it when
they're disappointed in me.

19:36.367 --> 19:39.000
My mom started saying my name
like it was all one word.

19:39.300 --> 19:41.033
Miranda Isabella Sanchez.

19:41.100 --> 19:42.934
Oof, I hate it when that happens.

19:43.000 --> 19:45.367
Sorry, my parents called you guys'
parents and ratted you out.

19:45.834 --> 19:48.533
That's okay. Parents are always
doing stuff like that.

19:48.734 --> 19:49.834
It's their code.

19:49.967 --> 19:51.667
So, I'm grounded for a week.

19:51.800 --> 19:52.967
How about you guys?

19:53.433 --> 19:56.266
Two weeks and I have
to write a 10-page paper

19:56.333 --> 19:57.834
on responsibility.

19:57.967 --> 19:59.233
Mm, what about you, Lizzie?

19:59.300 --> 20:00.767
Grounded for a week.

20:00.834 --> 20:02.900
But since I did save a human life,

20:03.166 --> 20:05.133
Mom's letting me go
to Matt's carnival tomorrow.

20:05.867 --> 20:08.834
Six hours of peeling kids
off a Velcro wall.

20:09.000 --> 20:12.133
JO: Honey, time to practice
for the carnival.

20:12.533 --> 20:13.533
Gotta go.

20:13.700 --> 20:14.800
-BOTH: Bye.
-Ugh.

20:16.300 --> 20:17.734
Okay, Matt. You ready?

20:17.834 --> 20:19.433
-[HELMET CLICKS LOCKED]
-Roger.

20:20.066 --> 20:21.166
Okay, let her rip.

20:27.734 --> 20:28.834
[GRUNTS]

20:29.266 --> 20:30.400
[WHOOPING]

20:30.467 --> 20:31.667
It works.

20:31.734 --> 20:33.166
Hey. All right.

20:33.233 --> 20:34.934
And look, it's not falling over
or anything.

20:35.033 --> 20:37.367
That is so cool. Can I try?

20:37.800 --> 20:40.000
Sure. Uh, let me get
your brother off the wall first.

20:42.533 --> 20:44.133
Yeah, it comes off too.

20:44.200 --> 20:45.200
[CHUCKLING]

20:47.300 --> 20:49.266
Oh, uh, hold on a second, Lizzie.

20:59.633 --> 21:01.600
[CREAKING]

21:06.333 --> 21:07.734
Oh, that was cool.

21:07.800 --> 21:09.934
Dad, help me up so I can go again.

21:11.133 --> 21:12.233
Dad?

21:12.300 --> 21:16.233
SAM: Jo, could you peel our daughter
off of the wall, please?

21:19.533 --> 21:20.600
LIZZIE: Hello?

21:24.100 --> 21:25.100
MALE CREW MEMBER 1: B-camera mark.

21:26.400 --> 21:27.500
Okay, new plan.

21:27.633 --> 21:28.867
[LAUGHING]

21:28.934 --> 21:30.133
MALE CREW MEMBER 2:
Okay, everybody, chillax.

21:30.533 --> 21:32.000
Somebody do something.

21:32.066 --> 21:34.767
[LAUGHING]
Oh, shoot! Lizzie, you had the CPR...

21:35.834 --> 21:37.500
[LAUGHS] Go, get help, Lizzie

21:37.567 --> 21:38.834
Liz... Lizzie, help that guy.

21:38.900 --> 21:40.000
-ASSISTANT DIRECTOR: Cut.
-MALE CREW MEMBER 3: Cut.

21:40.066 --> 21:42.233
Oh, my... Ew, ew, ew.

21:43.133 --> 21:44.133
MALE CREW MEMBER 4: Cut. Hey.

21:44.200 --> 21:45.800
Somebody besides me.

21:45.867 --> 21:47.900
I wanna talk to the stunt coordinator.

21:47.967 --> 21:48.967
Now.

21:49.033 --> 21:51.266
-[BLABBERS]
-[LAUGHING]

21:51.333 --> 21:52.433
Okay, here is what we do.

21:52.500 --> 21:53.967
We wait for the current show
to let out

21:54.033 --> 21:56.000
and then while
everyone's leaving the theatre...

21:56.400 --> 21:59.133
[BOTH LAUGHING]

21:59.433 --> 22:00.500
That's my arm.

22:00.567 --> 22:01.800
-ADAM LAMBERG: Okay.
-MALE CREW MEMBER 5: Don't cut.

22:02.967 --> 22:04.967
[THEME MUSIC PLAYING]
